{"title_page": "Zarina (artist)", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian artist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Zarina\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Zarina Hashmi\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1937|1|1}}\n| birth_place      = [[Aligarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India\n| death_date       = {{death date and given age|2020|4|25|83|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[London]], England\n| nationality      = India<br>United States\n| movement         = \n| awards           = \n| patrons          = \n| bgcolour         = \n| imagesize        = \n| field            = \n| training         = [[Stanley William Hayter|Atelier 17]]\n| works            = \n| influenced by    = \n| influenced       = \n| website          = {{URL|zarina.work}}\n}}\n\n'''Zarina Hashmi''' (1937<ref name=\"Phaidon Editors\">{{cite book |last1=Phaidon Editors |title=Great women artists |date=2019 |publisher=Phaidon Press |isbn=0714878774 |page=443}}</ref> \u2013 25 April 2020), known professionally as '''Zarina''', was an Indian-American artist and print maker based in [[New York City]]. Her work spanned drawing, printmaking, and sculpture. Associated with the Minimalist movement, her work utilized abstract and geometric forms in order to evoke a spiritual reaction from the viewer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zarina: Paper Like Skin|url=http://www.artic.edu/exhibition/zarina-paper-skin|publisher=Art Institute of Chicago|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Aligarh]], India, Zarina earned a degree in mathematics before studying a variety of printmaking methods in [[Thailand]], [[France]] (where she was apprenticed to [[Stanley William Hayter]]),<ref name=Ollman>{{cite web|last=Ollman|first=Leah|title=Zarina Hashmi|url=http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/reviews/zarina-hashmi/|work=Art in America|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref>  and printmaker [[T\u014dshi Yoshida]] in [[Tokyo]], Japan. <ref name=Galleryespace>{{cite web|title=Artist Bio: Zarina Hashmi|url=http://galleryespace.com/artists.php?artist=304|work=Gallery Espace|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> She lived and worked in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"Gallery Espace\">{{cite web |title=Zarina Hashmi |url=http://www.galleryespace.com/artists/gallery-espace/zarina-hashmi |website=Gallery Espace |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, Zarina served as a board member of the [[New York Feminist Art Institute]] and an instructor of papermaking workshops at the affiliated Women's Center for Learning. While on the editorial board of the feminist art journal ''[[Heresies:_A_Feminist_Publication_on_Art_and_Politics|Heresies]]'', she contributed to the \"Third World Women\" issue.<ref name=\"Heresies Collective\">{{cite web |title=Third World Women: The Politics of Being Other |url=http://heresiesfilmproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/heresies8.pdf |website=Heresies Collective |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nZarina died on 25 April 2020 in [[London]] at age 83.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/960250/artist-zarina-hashmi-dies-at-83|title=Artist Zarina Hashmi dies at 83|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\nZarina's art was informed by her identity as a [[Muslim]]-born Indian woman, as well as a lifetime spent traveling from place to place.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Wack! Art and the Feminist Revolution|last=Butler|first=Cornelia|publisher=MIT Press|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=320}}</ref> She used visual elements from Islamic religious decoration, especially the regular geometry commonly found in [[Islamic architecture]]. The abstract and spare geometric style of her early works has been compared to that of [[Minimalism|Minimalists]] such as [[Sol LeWitt]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nZarina's work explored the concept of home as a fluid, abstract space that transcends physicality or location. Her work often featured symbols that call to mind such ideas as movement, diaspora, exile. For example, woodblock print ''Paper Like Skin'' depicts a thin black line meandering upward across a white background, dividing the page from the bottom right corner to the top left corner. The line possesses a cartographic quality that, in its winding and angular division of the page, suggests a border between two places, or perhaps a [[topographical]] chart of a journey that is yet unfinished.<ref name=\"Guggenheim\">{{cite web |title=Zarina: Paper Like Skin |url=https://www.guggenheim.org/exhibition/zarina-paper-like-skin |website=Guggenheim |accessdate=11 January 2020 |date=25 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Selected exhibitions ==\nZarina was one of four artists/artist-groups to represent India in its first entry at the [[Venice Biennale]] in 2011.<ref name=\"Biennale\">{{cite web|url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/art/archive/54th-exhibition/first-time/india.html|title=Pavilion of India|publisher=La Biennale|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Hammer Museum]] in [[Los Angeles]] organized the first retrospective of her work in 2012.<ref name=\"Hammer\">{{cite web|url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/detail/exhibition_id/211|title=Zarina: Paper Like Skin|publisher=Hammer Museum|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref> Entitled ''Zarina: Paper Like Skin,'' the exhibition traveled to the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] and the [[Art Institute of Chicago]].<ref name=\"Luhring\">{{cite web|url=http://www.luhringaugustine.com/artists/zarina-hashmi|title=Artist Bio: Zarina Hashmi|work=Luhring Augustine|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref> \n\nDuring the 2017\u201318 academic year Zarina was the Artist-in-Residence at the Asian/Pacific/American Institute at [[NYU]].<ref name=\"nyu\">{{cite web |title=Asian/Pacific/American Institute Announces Zarina Hashmi As Artist-in-Residence 2017\u201318 |url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2017/august/asian-pacific-american-institute-announces-zarina-hashmi-as-arti.html |website=New York University |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref> The residency culminated in a solo exhibition, ''Zarina: Dark Roads'' (6 October 2017 \u2013 2 February 2018)<ref name=\"ArtAsiaPacific\">{{cite web |title=Zarina Hashmi Dark Roads |url=http://artasiapacific.com/Magazine/WebExclusives/ZarinaHashmiDarkRoads |website=ArtAsiaPacific |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref> and a publication, ''Directions to My House''.<ref name=\"New York University2\">{{cite web |title=\"Directions to My House\"--A Life Story through Words, Photographs, and Art |url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2018/october/-directions-to-my-house---a-life-story-through-words--photograph.html |website=New York University |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nExamples of her work are in the permanent art collections of the [[Museum of Modern Art]], the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], and [[Biblioth\u00e8que Nationale de France]].<ref name=\"Hammer\" /><ref name=\"Jeanne Bucher Jaeger\">{{cite web |title=Zarina |url=https://jeannebucherjaeger.com/artist/hashmi-zarina/ |website=Jeanne Bucher Jaeger |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.zarina.work/ Zarina's Website] \n* [https://www.luhringaugustine.com/artists/zarina images of Zarina's work] at Luhring Augustine Gallery, New York\n* [http://www.galleryespace.com/artists/gallery-espace/zarina-hashmi/ Gallery Espace, New Dehli, India]\n* [https://jeannebucherjaeger.com/artist/hashmi-zarina/ Jeanne Jaeger Bucher, Paris, France]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zarina}}\n\n[[Category:Indian printers]]\n[[Category:Indian lithographers]]\n[[Category:Women artists from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:1937 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Aligarh]]\n[[Category:Indian art critics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women artists]]\n[[Category:Indian women critics]]\n[[Category:American women artists of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American women printmakers]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women artists]]\n[[Category:Indian Muslims]]\n[[Category:American Muslims]]\n[[Category:Deaths in Greater London]]\n[[Category:Muslim artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian artist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Zarina\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Zarina Hashmi\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1937|1|1}}\n| birth_place      = [[Aligarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India\n| death_date       = {{death date and given age|2020|4|25|83|df=y}}\n| death_place      = [[London]], England\n| nationality      = India<br>United States\n| movement         = \n| awards           = \n| patrons          = \n| bgcolour         = \n| imagesize        = \n| field            = \n| training         = [[Stanley William Hayter|Atelier 17]]\n| works            = \n| influenced by    = \n| influenced       = \n| website          = {{URL|zarina.work}}\n}}\n\n'''Zarina Hashmi''' (1937<ref name=\"Phaidon Editors\">{{cite book |last1=Phaidon Editors |title=Great women artists |date=2019 |publisher=Phaidon Press |isbn=0714878774 |page=443}}</ref> \u2013 25 April 2020), known professionally by her first name only, was an Indian-American artist and print maker based in [[New York City]]. Her work spanned drawing, printmaking, and sculpture. Associated with the Minimalist movement, her work utilized abstract and geometric forms in order to evoke a spiritual reaction from the viewer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zarina: Paper Like Skin|url=http://www.artic.edu/exhibition/zarina-paper-skin|publisher=Art Institute of Chicago|accessdate=1 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Aligarh]], India, Zarina earned a degree in mathematics before studying a variety of printmaking methods in [[Thailand]], [[France]] (where she was apprenticed to [[Stanley William Hayter]]),<ref name=Ollman>{{cite web|last=Ollman|first=Leah|title=Zarina Hashmi|url=http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/reviews/zarina-hashmi/|work=Art in America|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref>  and printmaker [[T\u014dshi Yoshida]] in [[Tokyo]], Japan. <ref name=Galleryespace>{{cite web|title=Artist Bio: Zarina Hashmi|url=http://galleryespace.com/artists.php?artist=304|work=Gallery Espace|accessdate=23 November 2016}}</ref> She lived and worked in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"Gallery Espace\">{{cite web |title=Zarina Hashmi |url=http://www.galleryespace.com/artists/gallery-espace/zarina-hashmi |website=Gallery Espace |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, Zarina served as a board member of the [[New York Feminist Art Institute]] and an instructor of papermaking workshops at the affiliated Women's Center for Learning. While on the editorial board of the feminist art journal ''[[Heresies:_A_Feminist_Publication_on_Art_and_Politics|Heresies]]'', she contributed to the \"Third World Women\" issue.<ref name=\"Heresies Collective\">{{cite web |title=Third World Women: The Politics of Being Other |url=http://heresiesfilmproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/heresies8.pdf |website=Heresies Collective |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nZarina died on 25 April 2020 in [[London]] at age 83.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/latest/960250/artist-zarina-hashmi-dies-at-83|title=Artist Zarina Hashmi dies at 83|last=Staff|first=Scroll|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\nZarina's art was informed by her identity as a [[Muslim]]-born Indian woman, as well as a lifetime spent traveling from place to place.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=Wack! Art and the Feminist Revolution|last=Butler|first=Cornelia|publisher=MIT Press|year=2007|isbn=|location=|pages=320}}</ref> She used visual elements from Islamic religious decoration, especially the regular geometry commonly found in [[Islamic architecture]]. The abstract and spare geometric style of her early works has been compared to that of [[Minimalism|Minimalists]] such as [[Sol LeWitt]].<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nZarina's work explored the concept of home as a fluid, abstract space that transcends physicality or location. Her work often featured symbols that call to mind such ideas as movement, diaspora, exile. For example, woodblock print ''Paper Like Skin'' depicts a thin black line meandering upward across a white background, dividing the page from the bottom right corner to the top left corner. The line possesses a cartographic quality that, in its winding and angular division of the page, suggests a border between two places, or perhaps a [[topographical]] chart of a journey that is yet unfinished.<ref name=\"Guggenheim\">{{cite web |title=Zarina: Paper Like Skin |url=https://www.guggenheim.org/exhibition/zarina-paper-like-skin |website=Guggenheim |accessdate=11 January 2020 |date=25 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Selected exhibitions ==\nZarina was one of four artists/artist-groups to represent India in its first entry at the [[Venice Biennale]] in 2011.<ref name=\"Biennale\">{{cite web|url=http://www.labiennale.org/en/art/archive/54th-exhibition/first-time/india.html|title=Pavilion of India|publisher=La Biennale|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Hammer Museum]] in [[Los Angeles]] organized the first retrospective of her work in 2012.<ref name=\"Hammer\">{{cite web|url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/detail/exhibition_id/211|title=Zarina: Paper Like Skin|publisher=Hammer Museum|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref> Entitled ''Zarina: Paper Like Skin,'' the exhibition traveled to the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]] and the [[Art Institute of Chicago]].<ref name=\"Luhring\">{{cite web|url=http://www.luhringaugustine.com/artists/zarina-hashmi|title=Artist Bio: Zarina Hashmi|work=Luhring Augustine|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref> \n\nDuring the 2017\u201318 academic year Zarina was the Artist-in-Residence at the Asian/Pacific/American Institute at [[NYU]].<ref name=\"nyu\">{{cite web |title=Asian/Pacific/American Institute Announces Zarina Hashmi As Artist-in-Residence 2017\u201318 |url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2017/august/asian-pacific-american-institute-announces-zarina-hashmi-as-arti.html |website=New York University |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref> The residency culminated in a solo exhibition, ''Zarina: Dark Roads'' (6 October 2017 \u2013 2 February 2018)<ref name=\"ArtAsiaPacific\">{{cite web |title=Zarina Hashmi Dark Roads |url=http://artasiapacific.com/Magazine/WebExclusives/ZarinaHashmiDarkRoads |website=ArtAsiaPacific |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref> and a publication, ''Directions to My House''.<ref name=\"New York University2\">{{cite web |title=\"Directions to My House\"--A Life Story through Words, Photographs, and Art |url=https://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/news/2018/october/-directions-to-my-house---a-life-story-through-words--photograph.html |website=New York University |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nExamples of her work are in the permanent art collections of the [[Museum of Modern Art]], the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], and [[Biblioth\u00e8que Nationale de France]].<ref name=\"Hammer\" /><ref name=\"Jeanne Bucher Jaeger\">{{cite web |title=Zarina |url=https://jeannebucherjaeger.com/artist/hashmi-zarina/ |website=Jeanne Bucher Jaeger |accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.zarina.work/ Zarina's Website] \n* [https://www.luhringaugustine.com/artists/zarina images of Zarina's work] at Luhring Augustine Gallery, New York\n* [http://www.galleryespace.com/artists/gallery-espace/zarina-hashmi/ Gallery Espace, New Dehli, India]\n* [h